180325-161629"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gqual"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="genv"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Natural Environment</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gqual"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001002-20180325-161629"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Top of the News</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Why It Matters; Saving sewers from toxic water</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Eighteen companies were fined a total of $112,500 in a span of just four months, for dumping toxic industrial used water in sewers here.</Para><Para>Each firm was fined $3,500 to $13,500 between last November and February this year.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Among them was printing company Tat Seng Packaging Group, which was penalised for the fifth time.</Para><Para>Its multiple offences have raised questions on whether the fines are enough to deter companies from committing such pollutive acts.</Para><Para>Tat Seng Packaging Group was caught for its fifth offence when it discharged copper-tainted industrial used water in the sewerage system in September 2016. It was fined $12,000 in January this year for breach of the Sewerage and Drainage (Trade Effluent) Regulations.</Para><Para>The water it had discharged contained quantities of copper, a regulated metal, that exceeded the allowable limit by as much as three times.</Para><Para>Such offences are serious as public sewers convey used water to water reclamation plants for treatment before it is released into the environment, or for further purification into Newater - one of Singapore's four national taps.</Para><Para>Newater is used mainly for industrial and air-con cooling purposes, and is added to our reservoirs during dry weather.</Para><Para>ST_20180320_SBSEWER20US7T_3846849.jpg</Para><Para>Related Story</Para><Para>Recalcitrant printing firm fined for pollution</Para><Para>While measures are in place to ensure the safety of Newater, toxic substances in sewers can endanger the lives of staff, upset treatment processes and affect the quality of feedstock for Newater production, said national water agency PUB.</Para><Para>It noted that high concentrations of regulated metal substances and chemical compounds are toxic to the microorganisms which fuel the treatment process, and hence can disrupt operations at water reclamation plants.</Para><Para>Perhaps education and other forms of deterrence, such as a suspension of operations, similar to what is done to restaurants caught for hygiene lapses, could be considered to protect the environment, human health and water treatment processes.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Samantha Boh </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

